Note that t-conservative maps are not necessarily injective. The following is such an example:


\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    \bullet  \ar [r, dashed] & \bullet  \\
    \bullet  \ar [u] \ar [dr, dashed] & \\ 
    \bullet  \ar [u] \ar [r, dashed] & \bullet  \ar [uu]
  \end {tikzcd}

For any distributive lattice D, \operatorname {Spec} D is spectral. This gives us a functor
 \operatorname {Spec} : \mathbf {DL}^{\mathrm {op}} \to  \mathbf {Spec} 
from distributive lattices to spectral spaces.


It is then easy to see \mathbb {N} is Noetherian. Hence, by Theorem  prime ideals in \mathbb {N} are exactly meet-irreducible elements. According to this we can compute the spectrum of \mathbb {N} as below

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
\begin {tikzpicture}
  \node  (2) at (0,0) {2};
  \node  (3) at (1,0) {3};
  \node  (5) at (2,0) {5};
  \node  (p) at (3,0) {$\cdots $};

  \node  (4) at (0,1) {4};
  \node  (9) at (1,1) {9};
  \node  (25) at (2,1) {25};
  \node  (p2) at (3,1) {$\cdots $};

  \node  (8) at (0,2) {$\vdots $};
  \node  (27) at (1,2) {$\vdots $};
  \node  (125) at (2,2) {$\vdots $};
  \node  (pn) at (3,2) {$\vdots $};

  \node  (0) at (1.5,3) {0};

  \path [->] (2) edge (4);
  \path [->] (4) edge (8);
  \path [->] (8) edge (0);

  \path [->] (3) edge (9);
  \path [->] (9) edge (27);
  \path [->] (27) edge (0);

  \path [->] (5) edge (25);
  \path [->] (25) edge (125);
  \path [->] (125) edge (0);

  \path [->] (p) edge (p2);
  \path [->] (p2) edge (pn);
  \path [->] (pn) edge (0);
\end {tikzpicture}


where each number p above corresponds to the prime filter of those elements not containing p has a factor. Notice for any n\in \mathbb {N},
 O_n = \{p^k\mid p^k\not {\mid } n\}. 
Since each natural number only contains finitely many prime factors, it is easier to describe the closed sets,
 C_n = \{p^k\mid p^k \mid  n\} = \downarrow  p_1^{k_1} \cup  \cdots  \cup  \downarrow  p_m^{k_m}, 
where n = p_1^{k_1} \cdots  p_m^{k_m} is the prime factorisation of n.

\mathbb {N} also contains a sub distributive lattice \mathbb {P}, consisting of those numbers which does not contain a higher power of prime factor. By Proposition  \mathbb {P} is again Noetherian, and in fact a Heyting algebra again. The spectrum of \mathbb {P} is obtained by throwing out all the higher powers of primes in the spectrum of \mathbb {N},

  \usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
    \begin {tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
      \node  (2) at (0,0) {2};
      \node  (3) at (1,0) {3};
      \node  (5) at (2,0) {5};
      \node  (p) at (3,0) {$\cdots $};

      \node  (0) at (1.5,1) {0};

      \path [->] (2) edge (0);
      \path [->] (3) edge (0);
      \path [->] (5) edge (0);
      \path [->] (p) edge (0);
    \end {tikzpicture}


  \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {P} is homeomorphic to the usual ring spectrum \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {Z}, which is the one point compatification of the discrete space of natural numbers.

Algebraically, under Proposition , Theorem  means that for any finitely presented morphism D \to  E, its Booleanisation \lambda  D \to  \lambda  E has a left adjoint,

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
\begin {tikzcd}
  D & E \\
  {\lambda  D} & {\lambda  E}
  \arrow [from=1-1, to=1-2]
  \arrow [tail, from=1-1, to=2-1]
  \arrow [tail, from=1-2, to=2-2]
  \arrow [""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, from=2-1, to=2-2]
  \arrow [""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, curve={height=15pt}, from=2-2, to=2-1]
  \arrow ["\dashv "{anchor=center, rotate=-90}, draw=none, from=1, to=0]
\end {tikzcd}


given by taking the image of the constructible subset along \operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} D. Furthermore, since image of a map preserves binary intersections and unions, the left adjoint also preserves them. Hence, it will be a distributive lattice morphism, except the possibility that it does not preserve the top element.

A map f : D \to  E is a p-map iff f is weakly left orthogonal to 0 : 2[x] \to  2,

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    D \ar [d, "f"'] \ar [r] & {2[x]} \ar [d, "0"] \\ 
    E \ar [r] \ar [ur, dashed, "\exists "description] & 2
  \end {tikzcd}


Dually it is a q-map iff it is weakly left orthogonal to 1 : 2[x] \to  2.

  For any map f : D \to  E, let D \twoheadrightarrow  I/D \to  E be the dual of the pro-open,t-conservative factorisation. The closed set C_I = \operatorname {Spec} I/D (cf. Remark ) is the downward closure of the image of \operatorname {Spec} E in \operatorname {Spec} D, also the topological closure. In particular, the following are equivalent: 

The image of \operatorname {Spec} E is downward closed;

The image of \operatorname {Spec} E is closed;

The factorisation I/D \rightarrowtail  E is injective.

  For any f : D \to  E between distributive lattices, the following are equivalent:

f is a q-map;

\operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} D is a closed map between topological spaces.

  For a map f : D \to  E the following are equivalent:

f is a p-map;

For any x\in \operatorname {Spec} E, the induced map \uparrow  x \to  \uparrow  fx is surjective;

For any x\in \operatorname {Spec} E, it restricts to an injection at stalks,

  \usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
      \begin {tikzcd}
        D \ar [r, "f"] \ar [d, two heads] & E \ar [d, two heads] \\ 
        D/f^{-1}(x) \ar [r, tail] & E/x
      \end {tikzcd}

